{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-topic-topic-tsx","path":"/topics/corneal-superficial-injury/","result":{"data":{"firstChapter":{"id":"c405f1c0-4e8e-53c9-80f0-8af878326237","slug":"summary","fullItemName":"Summary","subChapters":[],"depth":1,"htmlHeader":"<!-- begin field ec330263-7299-4a45-bdf0-39401fc35b07 --><h1>Corneal superficial injury: Summary</h1><!-- end field ec330263-7299-4a45-bdf0-39401fc35b07 -->","htmlStringContent":"<!-- begin item 0faa7186-9479-40f0-847e-a4afbad7826c --><!-- begin field 9c5a59ab-466d-46bb-8193-ff521871c832 --><ul><li>Superficial corneal injuries are non-penetrating injuries affecting the outermost layer of the cornea.</li><li>Corneal abrasions are defects in the epithelial surface of the cornea — most heal in within 1–2 days.</li><li>Superficial corneal injuries typically present with sudden onset pain, discomfort or foreign body sensation of the eye and tearing.</li><li>The mechanism of injury and material involved should be determined, of particular importance are injuries due to chemicals, high-velocity foreign bodies or sharp objects.</li><li>There is usually a history of a precipitating event such as:<ul><li>An object striking the eye.</li><li>A foreign body entering the eye.</li><li>Difficult contact lens removal.</li></ul></li><li>Red flags for serious causes of red eye (such as significant changes in vision, significant trauma or marked eye pain, headache or photophobia) should be excluded.</li><li>The eye should be examined to:<ul><li>Exclude perforation or penetrating injuries.</li><li>Check visual acuity.</li><li>Identify foreign bodies — subtarsal foreign bodies should be sought by everting the upper eyelid.</li><li>Identify corneal abrasions — fluorescein should be used to stain the conjunctiva and cornea. An abrasion will stain fluoresce bright green with a cobalt-blue filter.</li></ul></li><li>Immediate referral to the emergency eye service is required for:<ul><li>A suspected penetrating eye injury or intraocular foreign body. All high-velocity injuries (for example due to hammering, chiselling, grinding, or lawn mowing), or injuries caused by sharp objects (for example glass, knives, thorns, darts, or pencils) should be treated as penetrating injuries until proven otherwise.</li><li>All chemical injuries. The affected eye should be immediately and copiously irrigated with normal saline or water for at least 20–30 minutes, and urgent ophthalmological assessment arranged.</li><li>A foreign body that cannot be removed or if the person is unable to tolerate examination.</li></ul></li><li>Other indications for immediate referral include:<ul><li>Any red flag symptom or sign for a serious eye condition such as severe pain, pupillary abnormalities or a significant reduction in visual acuity.</li><li>Hyphema (blood in the anterior chamber) or hypopyon (inflammatory exudate in the anterior chamber).</li><li>Large or deep abrasions.</li><li>Corneal opacities.</li></ul></li><li>Indications for discussion with ophthalmology regarding urgency of referral include:<ul><li>Recurrent erosion syndrome.</li><li>Superficial corneal injury due to contact lens use.</li><li>Persistent or worsening symptoms after 24 hours.</li><li>Rust rings that remain after removal of a metallic foreign body.</li></ul></li><li>Loose superficial foreign bodies should be removed if the expertise and equipment are available in primary care.</li><li>Analgesia and ocular lubricants should be offered for pain relief.</li><li>The need for topical antibiotics such as chloramphenicol to prevent secondary infection should be considered.</li><li>Advice should be given on suitable eye protection to prevent injury in the future. The person should be advised to avoid rubbing or touching the eye and contact lenses until the eye recovers.</li><li>Follow up should be arranged in 24 hours to ensure the abrasion is healing as expected — the person should be advised to seek urgent medical review if symptoms worsen or new features develop in the interim.</li></ul><!-- end field 9c5a59ab-466d-46bb-8193-ff521871c832 --><!-- end item 0faa7186-9479-40f0-847e-a4afbad7826c -->","topic":{"id":"2e6b8144-f211-5b68-b186-45133d37a07c","topicId":"2d59b81e-832a-46e3-9d29-6d51c4a5141f","topicName":"Corneal superficial injury","slug":"corneal-superficial-injury","aliases":[],"chapters":[{"id":"c405f1c0-4e8e-53c9-80f0-8af878326237","slug":"summary","fullItemName":"Summary","subChapters":[]},{"id":"6a87e9a1-1b9b-58c1-86d8-fe5ee1f34a4e","slug":"have-i-got-the-right-topic","fullItemName":"Have I got the right topic?","subChapters":[]},{"id":"16dcf024-1d0b-50df-8cf0-e74719b13ce8","slug":"how-up-to-date-is-this-topic","fullItemName":"How up-to-date is this topic?","subChapters":[{"id":"e61d3ac5-d7d6-5460-89d2-4e69efa4c406","slug":"changes","fullItemName":"Changes"},{"id":"5ec5fd5c-9db3-51d8-af8e-f6e8438761e4","slug":"update","fullItemName":"Update"}]},{"id":"7b3b7417-6d1b-5b24-a4e1-addce6978235","slug":"goals-outcome-measures","fullItemName":"Goals and outcome measures","subChapters":[{"id":"73e2859b-b945-53dd-8fee-44777b6eedb1","slug":"goals","fullItemName":"Goals"},{"id":"7257ef79-0ee6-5dd1-8f49-6cd9806a9644","slug":"outcome-measures","fullItemName":"Outcome measures"},{"id":"0b2acd6c-f0f7-56cc-b927-720a91bcac70","slug":"audit-criteria","fullItemName":"Audit criteria"},{"id":"ba1e3260-ca21-51ca-a0d1-9fdc9b116c31","slug":"qof-indicators","fullItemName":"QOF indicators"},{"id":"0209b951-b3a9-5c3c-a446-ddcd97c45330","slug":"qipp-options-for-local-implementation","fullItemName":"QIPP - Options for local implementation"},{"id":"820190fd-27f7-5d6b-b17d-c521e4d3bd23","slug":"nice-quality-standards","fullItemName":"NICE Quality standards"}]},{"id":"fc06b831-3b9c-52e0-a47e-afe2302e126c","slug":"background-information","fullItemName":"Background information","subChapters":[{"id":"b3af574b-6e1b-58ba-b821-a2467939e635","slug":"definition","fullItemName":"Definition"},{"id":"5db601f7-c0e9-5ad4-bcb6-b51ab2ade38f","s